<P><HI>Secondly, What &s;hall be rai&s;ed?</HI> The <HI>bodies</HI> of mankind. A man is &s;aid to die when the &s;oul is &s;eparated from the body, <HI>and returns unto God who gave it,</HI> Eccle&s;. xii 7. B<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">t it is the <HI>body</HI> only which is laid in the grave, and can be properly &s;aid to be <HI>rai<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ed:</HI> where|fore the <HI>re&s;urrection</HI> is, &s;t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ictly &s;peaking, competent to the body only. Moreover, it is the <HI>&s;ame</HI> body that dies. which &s;hall ri&s;e again. At the re&s;urrection, men &s;hall not appear with <HI>other</HI> b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">d<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">es for &s;ub&s;tance, than the&s;e which they now have, and which are &s;aid down in the grave: but with the <HI>&s;elf-&s;ame</HI> bodies endowed with other qualities. The very notion of a <HI>re&s;urrection</HI> implies thi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">;
